  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.5703" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <dateline>Oxford<lb/>87 Banbury Road<lb/>Ap. 11. 1887</dateline>
        <opener>Dear Schuchardt,</opener>

        <p>I have long been thinking of writing to you but somehow I never could get over my laziness. With regard to my Myfanwy’s infantile pronunciation I fear I never put it down (at any rate I cannot find it now) on paper and I am now fast forgetting what it was; but with regard to <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">ll</hi> I can state <pb facs="#IMG.2"
            n="2"/> for certain that she at first pronnced it <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">ss</hi>: she said <hi
            rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">San for Llan</hi>, and I can well remember a time when I prononced every <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">ll</hi> as <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">ss</hi>. My wife’s early pronunciation was <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">th thath</hi> for <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">llall</hi> (cf. <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">cylleth</hi> all over Wales for <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">cyllell</hi>), but one of her sisters pronounced <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">ll</hi> as <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">ss</hi> and said <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">arass</hi> for <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">arall</hi>. I should say that most Welsh children up to five years of age or thereabouts pronounce <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">ll</hi> as <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">ss</hi> or <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">th</hi>, mostly the former I think.</p>
        <pb facs="#IMG.3" n="3"/>
        <p>My children since they are in England here are fast forgetting <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.902">Welsh</ref> as their early language: it is very difficult to prevent that though of course they can read and pronounce it perfectly and on account of it they have never had any trouble with the pronunciation of German consonants, exceph <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
ch</hi> pal.l<note n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">Der palatale <hi
              rend="unknown" rendition="#none">ch</hi>-Laut kommt im <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.902">Kymrischen</ref> nicht vor.</note> I hear my friend Mr. Morfill<note
            n="2" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName
              ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2234">William Richard Morfill</persName> (1834–1909), Slavist, lehrte in <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.5054">Oxford</ref>, erhielt 1889 eine Dozentur und wurde 1900 zum Professor ernannt.</note> sometimes talking of your work on the borders of Slavonic. I am myself just now trying to get ready for the press <pb
            facs="#IMG.4" n="4"/> a small work on Celtic mythology.<note n="3" place="foot" type="editorial">Vermutlich <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.6399">Rhŷs, John. 1888. 'Lectures on the Origin and Growth of Religion as illustrated by Celtic Heathendom (The Hibbert Lectures, 1886)'. London: Williams and Norgate</ref>

            </bibl>. Das „small work“ umfasste allerdings am Ende über 700 Seiten (mit Indices).</note> Mrs. Rhys and <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5032">Myfanwy</persName> wish to be kindly remembered to you. Myfanwy has a sister of ten, so we are four altogether. You will be sorry to hear that my wife has had a great deal of <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.5566">illness</ref> since we left <placeName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.6047">Wales</placeName>: she is pretty well just now</p>
        <closer>
          <salute>Yours very truly</salute>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2510">John Rhys</persName>
          </signed>
        </closer>
      </div>
